<div id="review_2444033285" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2444033285" />
    <a title="Monica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4739465-monica"><img alt="Monica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577896647p2/4739465.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2444033285?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monica" href="/user/show/4739465-monica">Monica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12403860-the-ways-of-white-folks">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=aoc">aoc</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=kindle_fiction">kindle_fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=pub-b4_1950">pub-b4_1950</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=short-story_collections">short-story_collections</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=5-star">5-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=aoc-male">aoc-male</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=racial-matters">racial-matters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=soc-sci-politics">soc-sci-politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2444033285" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3462862092561386661">Hughes lives up to the hype!! I absolutely loved this book.  A relativistic time capsule showcasing what it meant to be black in America in a world of whiteness in the 1930s.  Hughes has compiled a set of stories that echo the sentiments that we see now.  While I would not call this book prescient, I would say that it has tremendous historical value. We see the seeds of behaviors and attitudes in the now, that were the norm back in Hughes time.  A history book which demonstrates that yes, we act</span>
  <span id="freeText3462862092561386661" style="display:none">Hughes lives up to the hype!! I absolutely loved this book.  A relativistic time capsule showcasing what it meant to be black in America in a world of whiteness in the 1930s.  Hughes has compiled a set of stories that echo the sentiments that we see now.  While I would not call this book prescient, I would say that it has tremendous historical value. We see the seeds of behaviors and attitudes in the now, that were the norm back in Hughes time.  A history book which demonstrates that yes, we actually have made some racial progress in the last 90 years by comparison. That is to say, things are better than they were. That is not to say that the work is done. There is still so much progress yet to be made on the subject of race and of white supremacy. Also, the book though more historical than modern, does not seem at all dated. A veritable study in cultural relativism.  Cultural relativism is the view that all beliefs, customs, and ethics are relative to the individual within his own social context. The book showcases the behaviors, norms and traditions within the white culture on treatment of blacks. The perspective of the book is from black culture. The title says it all. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /> <br /><b>Summary</b><br /> <br /> <br /><u><b>Cora Unashamed</b></u> - Really great start!! Cora is a servant/slave to a family in an all white rural enclave. She is trapped by economic and familial circumstances. In her life, she comes to love one of the children of the family she works for. That child has an unplanned event that leads to her death, a side effect arranged by the family she works for to save their reputations. Cora can't be silent anymore. <b>Analysis</b>: So powerful, talks about the invisibility of black folks in service to whites (maid, nanny, cook). Also shines a light into the homes of blacks that make it impossible to uplift. Pressures families put on themselves in addition to the treatment of blacks in the era. This story is also about abortion and about the stigma associated with a premarital pregnancy and the lengths a family will go to prevent scandal. Lastly it looks at the moral redline in which Cora could no longer work for the family. Very affecting.<br /> <br /><u><b>Slave on the Block</b></u> - A story about how well meaning, well intentioned, wealthy white folks. This story has a white folks/couple patting themselves on the back for being so open and free with the negro help. The couple hires a black maid and a black young man for a gardener/house help. The white wife is an artist who become fascinated with the young man. She has been using him as a model for her painting called "Slave on the Block" and yes, it is exactly like it sounds. The maid who is older takes a romantic interest in the younger man. The young man develops hubris by treatment by all the women and creates a lot of turbulence in the house. The husband thinks of himself as not racist but isn't comfortable with the behaviors. The husbands mother comes to visit and is put off by the rudeness of the young man. The husband fires the young man much to his wife's and maid's dismay. <b>Analysis</b>: Powerful story! This story showcases the way that white people look at blacks as a sort of fetish. In a way overcompensating for the ill treatment of negroes on the whole. There is some associative guilt mixed with a lot amount of patronizing. They (negroes) can't help who they are. They need understanding white folks to help them be civil and intelligent. A sort of passive aggressive racism. Hughes so far is pretty amazing!<br /> <br /><u><b>Home</b></u> - A black musician who is seriously ill returns home in the South after living in Europe for 8 years. He's forgotten the rules of engagement in America and the results are tragic. <b>Analysis</b>: Hughes demonstrates a deftness for worldbuilding here. He creates the environment in which the musician is in and you get to know who he is. He is going home to die (though that is never explicitly stated). While he is home, he gives music lessons, and a white female music teacher is a fan of his. He makes the mistake of touching her hand in public and is lynched for it. Showcases the awful racism of the South.<br /><br /><br /><u><b>Passing</b></u> - Story of a young man passing who sees his mother in public and cannot acknowledge her. He is both guilt ridden and proud that he is being engulfed into the world of white people. <b>Analysis</b>: An epistolary story where a young man who is passing sees his mother. He is with his fiancé who has no idea he is passing. The letter states his love and pride in his life but also laments his inability to interact with his mother about his life decisions. A sad but an effective story.<br /> <br /><u><b>A Good Job Gone</b></u> - a black butler (?) laments the loss of his job because his white, married employer got caught up in an affair with a black woman who ultimately scorned him. <b>Analysis</b>: The white man in the story is a lothario who doesn't seem to have issues with color. He pretty much likes all women. He's married to a paralyzed woman so his infidelities are somehow excused or rather he shows no guilt or remorse. He falls for a black woman who fools around with him because he buys her things but has no long-term interest in him. Of course, the reason he is a successful lothario is because of his money. The butler was a go between. Once the woman was gone, the butler was a reminder. This one was not so much about racism but about the callousness associated with wealth. I got the impression that the lothario would have treated anyone the same in this story regardless of skin color. <br /> <br /><u><b>Rejuvenation Through Joy</b></u> - A weird one with two men creating a colony (health spa) by infuse its guests with the rhythms of negroes because negroes are always happy. So they brought people in to listen to the music and poetry and dance and it rejuvenated them. This was the poshest of spas. Twist at the end. <b>Analysis</b>: This one is again a fetishization of blacks in the form of a scam. White folks in this story pay top dollar to have the healing energy and peace of mind that black people have. They have been sold an opportunity to take in the black rhythms and sounds and dance to achieve this bliss. A sucker born every minute. The cherry on top of this sundae is that the main attraction of this spa seemed to be a reclusive man with air of haughtiness. Turns out he was probably black. I'm loving these time capsules through different eyes..."<br /> <br /><u><b>The Blues I'm Playing</b></u> - Very wealthy older white woman becomes a patron of the arts. Her fondest artist is a black female pianist. The patron has her own ideas about the pianist's future. The pianist forges her own path much to the patron's surprise. <b>Analysis</b>: Patronizing white folks who know what's best for black folk. White woman tries to live vicariously through a black woman who doesn't share the same goals or appreciate the same things. A demonstration of a white person who believes they are open minded and above prejudice yet tries to <s>guide</s> control a black person because of the belief that black folks just don't know what's best for them. In the end, much to the dismay of the white patron, the young pianist chooses to marry and have children and play the blues rather than become a renowned classical pianist that the patron wanted.<br /> <br /><u><b>Red-Headed Baby</b></u> - Short story about a white seaman who has a port of call in a nowhere place. He had been there before 3 years ago and found entertainment with a young black woman. Guess what happens? <b>Analysis</b>: A very common story. In this particular case women are used and disposed of. A black woman is the lowest form of woman and one he would never have had to do with except she was the only "thing" available to him. He returns expecting a repeat romp and finds that he has a son from the first encounter. He wants nothing to do with it. This one seemed to have more to do with men than with race…<br /> <br /><u><b>Poor Little Black Fellow</b></u> - wealthy white couple takes the orphan of their black servants under their wings. He's almost like a son but for his skin color. They raised him from 5 and patted themselves on the back for how generous they were. He grows up and fell for a white woman in Europe. Their reaction was...predictable. <b>Analysis</b>: This one reminded me of a quote I read in an essay once about an Asian woman who was adopted by a white family. <blockquote>"No matter where you are from, when you are adopted and nonwhite you become, to many, a symbol of the magnanimity of white Americans." ~ <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33932361.Nasty_Women_Feminism__Resistance__and_Revolution_in_Trump_s_America" title="Nasty Women Feminism, Resistance, and Revolution in Trump's America by Samhita Mukhopadhyay" rel="nofollow noopener">Nasty Women: Feminism, Resistance, and Revolution in Trump's America</a></blockquote> Oftentimes the folks lives are better, but one does get the impression that these folks are doing this to feel better about themselves rather than concern for the child or the deceased parents. They have deemed the child to have less value but for them. This perception clearly hasn't changed much though the price disappointment back then compared to now may be less voracious. It's not quite taken for granted that all whites are superior. Not like it was in the 30s. <br /> <br /><u><b>Little Dog</b></u> - Lonely middle-aged white lady buys a dog for companionship and has his meat delivered by the janitor who is black. She became intrigued by him and his family. <b>Analysis</b>: This was another story that had less to do with race than with general obsession. A lonely white lady became preoccupied imagining the life of a man who was kind to her. I'm not convinced it was his blackness that intrigued her more than his innate kindness in spite of his economic obstacles. Also, he was male, and she was lonely. In the end she moved, but I think that was more out of discomfort for being attracted to a black married man rather than just a black man.<br /> <br /><u><b>Berry</b></u> - a young, uneducated black man goes to work and a disabled children's home. The staff and administration take him for granted and/or ignore him, but the children love him. An unexpected event occurs and guess who they blame. <b>Analysis</b>: Blacks as scapegoats. Racism does have its benefits. I was reminded of a quote from <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/31817749.The_Stone_Sky__The_Broken_Earth___3_" title="The Stone Sky (The Broken Earth, #3) by N.K. Jemisin" rel="nofollow noopener">The Stone Sky</a>,<blockquote>"But for a society built on exploitation, there is no greater threat than having no one left to oppress."</blockquote> <br /><br /><u><b>Mother and Child</b></u> - a town that comfortably racially intermingled but times are changing because one of the black men has fathered a child with a white woman. The father has run off to keep from being lynched. The mother died in childbirth. <b>Analysis</b> Everyone is open minded until consensual sex with a person of color causes the town folk to re-evaluate their lenient stance. Not as free from bigotry as they thought.<br /> <br /><u><b>One Christmas Eve</b></u> - Little black boy wants desperately to see Santa Claus in a predominately white rural town. <b>Analysis</b>: A story about a young boy learning a hard lesson about growing up black in a 1934 America. Definitely a second-class citizen, his mother has to explain to him why he can't see Santa and can't have toys. Her white employers have shorted her pay that week so that their own children could enjoy Christmas. Their callous disregard of her personal situation is telling and familiar. It also covers the squashing of a childhood fantasy of Santa. Santa becomes an avatar for white privilege in this story. The black kid does not get to have the luxury of believing.<br /> <br /><u><b>Father and Son</b></u> - Miscegenation in the Jim Crow South 1930s with a son that wants the perks that come with whiteness. This story was the most vicious because it is probably the best detailing of what the South was like for black people in the 1930s. In this story, slavery was abolished but the perceptions and opinions of blacks had not changed. They were still treated as property. One boy son of a plantation owner and his black concubine (boy's mother) wants to claim his birthright. He is proud, stubborn, educated and looks very much like his father. In fact, could pass for white. He comes home from school and begins pushing his father to recognize him as a son. He begins to take liberties among the household and things come to a head. The father refuses to acknowledge any of his children and especially not the one that looks like him. Things come to a head and his father ends up dead and the town catches up and lynches the son. Since it is the Jim Crow South, they also lynch his brother for being a black male in the household. <b>Analysis</b>: Full on racist behavior bordering on slavery. We see miscegenation being expected and the byproducts being completely devalued and disrespected by the man who exploits the black condition. There is no self-awareness here, only white supremacy. We also see that blacks are becoming more educated and in doing so are recognizing the in justice and hypocrisy and exploitation of the status quo. In the South, standing up mean death even by your own father. That is the strength and persistence of white supremacy. The alternative is submission. This is what the father was demanding.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Langston Hughes continues to support my burgeoning theory that poets make superb writers. His writing is immersive. I found myself captivated by this book published in the year my father was born and to be honest, I saw a lot of my father in the characterizations and the language (could be nostalgia. I miss my dad and there were snippets of his world here). There is a smoothness in the writing that was reminiscent. As I mentioned, the stories focus on the way black people characterize white people, so in this collection, "White folks gonna white folk". Hughes treats the black folks in his stories differently. His assessments are not as harsh for their actions. He lets the white folks do the judging here and the reader gets to judge their judgment. This is a fantastic classic that stands up to the test of time!! There is much more Hughes in my future!!<br /><br /><i>4.5+ Stars</i><br /><br />Read on kindle</span>
  <a data-text-id="3462862092561386661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
